bury, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Ramsbury, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Korean Kyong, Kyong Suk, Young, Chae, Chi Young, Hang, Kil, Rin, Sang Hun, Chang, Chong, Insoo, Kum, Sun Young, Yom, Young Hwan.  Cambodian Kiwan, Oeurn, Phoeun, Pich, Saroeuth, Seung, Sophath, Sophea, Yoeun, Phan, Son.  Indian Shanti, Harendra.","Indian (Uttar Pradesh): Brahmin name, from Sanskrit <i>om</i>, the Hindu sacred and mystic syllable uttered at the beginning of prayers.","Cambodian: written ឱម, corresponding to the exclamation of solemn affirmation, of Sanskrit origin (see 1 above), chanted by Buddhist monks."],"variants":[{"name":"Oum","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Southeast Asian Heang, Hye, Kam, Kan, Kheng, Khin, Kun, Sang, Sok, Phong, Yom, Yoo, Youn, Cuong, Phal, Samnang, Tin.  Cambodian Sokha, Chheang, Choeun, Moeun, Roeun, Sambath, Samoeun, Savuth, Soeun, Sopheap.","Cambodian: written អ៊ុំ, from a Khmer word denoting an elder sibling of one's parent (i.e. ‘uncle’ or ‘aunt’). Compare   Om   3 and   Um   2."]}]},{"name":"Ramsbury","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: possibly a habitational name from a place so named near Gunzenhausen, Franconia. This surname is not found in Germany.","Alternatively, perhaps an altered form of German <b>Ramsberg</b> or <b>Ramsberger</b>: habitational name from any of several places in southern Germany called Ramsberg. The surname <i>Ramsberg</i> is very rare in Germany."],"variants":[{"name":"Ransburg","meanings":["German: variant of   Ramsburg  . This surname is very rare in Germany."]},{"name":"Remsberg","meanings":["Altered form of German <b>Ramsberg</b> or <b>Ramsberger</b> (see   Ramsburg  ), or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]}]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Matilda of Ramsbury was born about 1067, in Ramsbury, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Roger of Salisbury about 1089, in Salisbury, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in Salisbury, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1067–":"umbes 1067–Surnud","1065–1139":"1065–1139","1085–Female":"1085–Surnud","1107–1139":"1107–1139","1067–Female":"1067–Surnud","1107":"1107","1139":"1139","Abt 1067":"umbes 1067","Abt 1089":"umbes 1089","1067":"1067","1065":"1